Q: Why Tailwind extension &quot;Tailwind CSS IntelliSence&quot; does not work in tailwind v4.1.18(React js vite) A: <p>**Warning! The reason why the extension does not work is not official, I only propose. However the solution does work.</p>
<p>Reason:**<br />
I think the problem is in the difference of connecting the Taiwindcss to react, in later versions it was through tailwind.config.js example:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
export default {
  content: [
    &quot;./index.html&quot;,
    &quot;./src/**/*.{js,jsx}&quot;,
  ],
  theme: {
    extend: {},
  },
  plugins: [],
}
</code></pre>
<p>But in the latest version <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/79854690/why-tailwind-extension-tailwind-css-intellisence-does-not-work-in-tailwind-v4">v4.1.18</a>, official tailwind website <a href="https://tailwindcss.com/docs/installation/using-vite" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://tailwindcss.com/docs/installation/using-vite</a> suggests to connect through vite.config.js example:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>import { defineConfig } from 'vite'
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react'
import tailwindcss from &quot;@tailwindcss/vite&quot;

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react(),
    tailwindcss(),
  ],
})
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br />
The solution is very simple. We need to open an empty tailwind.config.js file. And that is it.</p>
<p><strong>Info:</strong><br />
I do not know if it is the best solution, and i would be very happy to see other solutions, and official reasons</p>
